                <h2>The Battle of Quebec: September 13,1759</h2>
                <div>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="Images/BolducFamilyHistory/TheBattle/TheBattle_900.jpg" title="The Battle of Quebec" alt="The Battle of Quebec" />
                        <figcaption>The Battle of Quebec</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                </div>
                <p>This is a hand colored original print of the Battle of Quebec. It was first produced and published in the 1760 edition of The "London"  Magazine.  It was purchased in 1957 before the restored Louis Bolduc House was opened to the public.</p>
                <p>It needs some special attention.    The print is not archivally framed so it is vulnerable to deterioration caused by                                         fluctuations in temperature, humidity, and light. It will cost around $350 to address the preservation needs of this wonderful print.</p>

                <p>The English and the French are fighting here.  The English won the battle.</p>
                <p>Here we meet some of the major players for the American Revolution in the French & Indian War - research George Washington, for starters.</p>
                <p>As a result of this battle in the Seven Years War (as it is known in Europe  (known as the French & Indian War in North America),  Spain got the French territory west of the Mississippi River and New Orleans.   Spain got Ste. Genevieve- it was a hush-hush preemptive treaty between the two Bourbon ruled countries to prevent those heretic Protestant Englishmen from getting any more French territory than was absolutely necessary. This is how England got Canada and Illinois which it attached to Virginia. England also got India - which France lost. </p>
                <p>The Indians were promised (by England) that they would be able to live forever in the North West Territories i.e. Ohio and Indiana - oh well, that didn't last long at all.</p>

                <p>We do not know if Louis Bolduc was wounded.</p>
                <p>His house was burned down - we even have a shingle from one of the burned down Bolduc houses - his uncle's, we think - in a frame in our Bolduc House.  </p>
                <p>He did decide to leave Quebec with his wife, Marguerite and their baby son, Louis.</p>
                <p>We know he died in 1815 and is buried in the Memorial Cemetery in Ste. Genevieve.</p>
                <p>Since he is descended from educated men, certainly Louis Bolduc was educated as well– explore what we do and don’t know about him and his family.</p>
